  "advice": "Alright Tom, let's get you set for a productive week before we dive into the structured plan.\n\n**Fitness Assessment**\nYour recent runs demonstrate a solid aerobic base, consistently maintaining an average heart rate within Zone 2 (141-154 bpm) across various paces from 9:00-10:30/mi. Your power output, consistently between 232-266W, further confirms a steady effort level during these easy runs. This consistency in aerobic development is a strong foundation as we head into structured training.\n\n**This Week's Focus**\nThis week remains focused on easy aerobic running to solidify your base before the official plan begins. Aim to keep your average heart rate firmly within Zone 2 (124-154 bpm) for all runs, letting your pace naturally adjust. Given the rainy and warm weather, don't be surprised if your pace is a bit slower than usual while maintaining the target heart rate.\n\n**Key Priorities**\n*   **Maintain Aerobic Zone:** Keep your average heart rate firmly in Zone 2 (124-154 bpm) on all runs to maximize aerobic development.\n*   **Gradual Mileage Build:** Aim to gently increase your weekly mileage from last week's 2.5 miles to around 8-10 miles, preparing for the structured plan next week.\n*   **Listen to Conditions:** Be mindful of the warm, rainy, and windy conditions expected this week; adjust your effort and pace accordingly to stay within your target HR zones.\n\n**Watch Out For**\nThe sharp drop in weekly mileage to 2.5 miles last week, following a 14.2-mile week, highlights a need for consistent training volume. Ensure you build back gently this week to avoid starting the official plan with a significant gap in your recent running routine.\n\n**Upcoming Milestones**\nLook forward to officially starting your Hal Higdon Novice 2 Marathon Plan on Monday, June 29th, which will introduce more structure and specific workouts like long runs and pace work to your training."
